mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Middle English <i>mody</i> ‘proud, haughty, angry, fierce, bold, brave, or rash’ (Old English <i>mōdig</i>). Compare   Muddiman  . This English name has been established in Ireland since the late 13th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Woody","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ + <i>heie</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>wudu</i> + <i>(ge)hæg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived by an enclosure in a wood, or habitational, for a person from a place so named, such as Woodhey Green in Faddiley (Cheshire). Also possibly from East Woodhay (Hampshire) and West Woodhay (Berkshire), apparently named with Old English <i>wīd</i> ‘wide, broad’ as the initial element, confused with early Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’, and so too with Old English <i>wudu</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>wodi</i> or some other derivative of Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘frenzied, wild’ (Old English <i>wōd</i>), perhaps formed on the analogy of, for example, Middle English <i>mody</i> (see   Moody  ). Compare   Wood   2."]},{"name":"Muddiman","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): nickname from Middle English <i>mody</i> ‘proud, haughty, angry, fierce, bold, brave, rash’ (Old English <i>mōdig</i>) + <i>man</i> ‘man’. See   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Mooty","meanings":["English: variant of   Moody  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Mutig</b>, a nickname meaning ‘cheerful’."]},{"name":"Moodie","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Moudy","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Moody  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Mowdy","meanings":["English or Irish: variant of   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Mudie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Iain.","English and Scottish (Angus): variant of   Moody  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":71,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705210,"age":100,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the Briti